This first day of fall yesterday had me doing some serious reminiscing. A few months ago I was so upset over what this summer would be with everything shut down or cancelled. Now it‚Äôs crazy to say...that may have been the best summer of my life. Normally this type A planner is stressed about planning each festival and event into our schedule. It was so REFRESHING to have no plans!!! We found so much joy in simpler things. Exploring outside, water fights, walks, parks, family dinner every single night and those sanity saving distanced bonfires! I hope when the world starts going back to how it used to be, I can remember how wonderful it was to just slow down and enjoy the little moments üíï#pleaseremindmethough #weknowplannerstephwillreturn

üíóMonth 2üíó

2 months old!! This entire month was spent physically distancing at home. The isolation really sucks and there have been many tears shed. HAPPY EASTER EVERYONE!! This year was definitely different to keep everyone safe and healthy. But we still had a wonderful weekend with zoom dinners, an egg hunt in the snow, a super excited toddler after finding his basket, distanced visits with loved ones and so many delicious treats dropped off on our porch! We may be physically isolated right now, but I found that the love and appreciation for family was stronger this year than ever before üíï

I thought it was safer for Dido if I dropped off his care package instead of Will yesterday. So I took the 1 minute drive to his house (for the first time ‚Äúout‚Äù without the kids since Jules was born) and I got to say hello...from a safe distance. We‚Äôre both feeling pretty lonely and isolated, so it filled my heart to see my daddy! üíï #newnormal #physicaldistancingsocialconnecting

I don‚Äôt really know how to express all the feelings I‚Äôm having...but here goes! I‚Äôm of course grateful to be on maternity leave right now, but I also feel guilty that I‚Äôm not there with my work family. Everyday I am worried about my RAH and NE coworkers who put themselves at risk for the safety of others. It breaks my heart that the public is told to quarantine for 14 days after coming into contact with COVID-19, and my coworkers have to make the choice of returning home to their loved ones knowing they came in contact. I‚Äôve had some friends who have decided to isolate themselves from their own children so that they can continue helping the public. So, THANK YOU! Thank you to the Nurses, Doctors, EMS, RTs, Social workers, Unit clerks, Service workers, Environmental services, DI techs, Registration, Educators and Management. Thank you for your bravery, your commitment, your skills, and your strength during this time. Thank you for putting the needs of the public above your own. Thank you for truly being heroes! #covid_19 #therealheroes
üíóMonth 1üíó
